{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502555"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:46:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:46:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1874"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1874"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.24,0.38,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1874"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39767"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16457"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of dizzy spells and feeling light-headed. He has no other symptoms and is otherwise in good health. He has a medical history of hypertension. His medications include amlodipine. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks four glasses of wine at weekends. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The physical examination is otherwise unremarkable. Laboratory investigations reveal a haemoglobin of 93 g/L (128-175). A CT scan is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Carcinoma of the stomach","Carcinoma of the pancreas","Retroperitoneal sarcoma","Renal cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a large mass in the head of the pancreas (Image 1) and a distended gallbladder consistent with biliary obstruction (Image 2). These findings, combined with the patient\u0027s presentation of unexplained anaemia, are most consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the pancreas\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile pancreatic cancer typically presents with weight loss, anorexia, and abdominal pain, it can also present with vague symptoms such as anaemia, as seen in this case. The distended gallbladder suggests impending biliary obstruction, which can lead to Courvoisier\u0027s sign (a palpable gallbladder in the presence of painless jaundice).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the stomach\u003C/strong\u003E could present similarly with anaemia, but symptoms like anorexia, nausea, and weight loss are more common. The CT images do not show a gastric mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrointestinal stromal tumours\u003C/strong\u003E (GISTs) can cause anaemia and are often found incidentally on imaging. However, they are most commonly found in the stomach and appear as exophytic masses, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetroperitoneal sarcomas\u003C/strong\u003E typically become symptomatic when they grow large enough to compress surrounding structures. Symptoms are usually vague and can include abdominal fullness, shortness of breath, or leg swelling. The CT images do not show a retroperitoneal mass consistent with sarcoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is often asymptomatic and discovered incidentally on imaging. When symptomatic, it may present with haematuria, flank pain, or a palpable mass. The CT images do not show a renal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the CT scan was an appropriate initial investigation for unexplained anaemia, especially given the patient\u0027s age and smoking history, which increase the risk of gastrointestinal malignancy. The findings of a pancreatic mass with associated biliary obstruction strongly support the diagnosis of pancreatic cancer as the cause of this patient\u0027s anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anaemia is a well-recognised mode of presentation for carcinoma of the pancreas.","CT scan can be an appropriate initial investigation for unexplained anaemia, especially when gastrointestinal malignancy is suspected.","A distended gallbladder in the presence of a pancreatic mass suggests biliary obstruction."],"references":["Park  W, Chawla A, O\u0027Reilly E. Pancreatic Cancer A Review. JAMA 2021; 326:851-62. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9363152/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39767"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1874"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18515"},{"type":"media","id":"18516"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20346"},{"type":"media","id":"20347"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18515"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8bd34be-f228-493a-b2df-75abc6bd31fc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8bd34be-f228-493a-b2df-75abc6bd31fc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":673,"hei